ave affected political socialization, political attitudes and practices, and levels of political participation among the foreign born and native born, she offers new findings that are often at odds with the conventional wisdom emphasizing the role socioeconomic status plays in political involvement. Fluid Borders includes the voices of many individuals, offers exciting new research on Latina women indicating that they are more likely than men to vote and to participate in political activities, and considers how the experience of social stigma affects the collective identification and political engagement of members of marginal groups. This innovative study points the way toward a better understanding of the Latino political experience, and how it differs from that of other racial groups, by situating it at the intersection of power, collective identity, and place.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aHispanic AmericanszCaliforniazLos AngelesvInterviews. 0aHispanic AmericanszCaliforniazLos AngelesxEthnic identity. 0aHispanic AmericanszCaliforniazLos AngelesxPolitics and government. 0aHispanic AmericanszCaliforniazLos AngelesxSocial conditions. 0aPower (Social sciences)zCaliforniazLos Angeles. 0aSocial classeszCaliforniazLos Angeles. 0aWorking classzCaliforniazLos AngelesvInterviews. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Emigration & Immigration.2bisacsh  aamerican borders.  acalifornia.  acollective identity.  alargest minority group.  alatina women.  alatino experience.  alatino identity.  alatinos.  alos angeles.  amarginal groups.  amiddle class.  amontebello.  anonfiction study.  apersonal interviews.  apersonal power.  apolitical attitudes.  apolitical engagement.  apolitical identity.  apolitical participation.  apolitical socialization.  aracial minorities.  as